  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Key Regulatory Requirements:\n- Implementing Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Conducting customer due diligence\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Reporting suspicious activities\n- Performing risk assessments\n\n2. Major Legislation:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n\n3. Specific Compliance Measures:\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Monitoring unusual transactions\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Implementing internal control systems\n- Conducting regular staff training\n\n4. Potential Consequences of Non-Compliance:\n- Significant financial penalties\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\n5. International Standards:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Global regulatory cooperation frameworks\n\nFinancial institutions must proactively work to prevent money laundering through comprehensive compliance programs and ongoing monitoring.",
